# Bandit Level 9

## Goal
Find the password stored in data.txt — a binary file.
The password is one of the few human-readable strings preceded by "=" signs.

## What I learned
- How to extract readable text from binary files using `strings`
- How to combine strings with grep to narrow down results
- Why == appears next to the password (used as a marker)
- Trial and error is a valid approach — try, see results, refine

## My Approach

```bash
# First extracted all readable text from the binary file
strings data.txt

# Got too many results — used grep to narrow it down
# First tried one = sign
strings data.txt | grep "="

# Still too many results — refined to ==
strings data.txt | grep "=="

# One clean result — password found!
```

## What I learned from trial and error
First tried `grep "="` — returned too many results.
Then tried `grep "=="` — returned just the password line.

## Breaking down the command

```
strings data.txt  ← extract all readable text from binary file
|                 ← pipe output into grep
grep "=="         ← find only lines containing ==
```

## Why == appears
The password lines were formatted like:
`========== thepassword`
The == signs were markers to help identify the real password
among all the random readable text strings pulled out.


## Key commands learned
| Command | What it does |
|---------|-------------|
| `strings file` | Extract readable text from binary file |
| `strings file | grep "=="` | Find specific readable text in binary |

